00:06:23.280 --> 00:06:25.950
The Cosmos asked whether
gravitational forces

00:06:25.950 --> 00:06:28.460
are about the mass or density
of the gravitational source.

00:06:28.460 --> 00:06:30.540
Answer-- once you're
outside the gravitating

00:06:30.540 --> 00:06:32.070
object, what matters is mass.

00:06:32.070 --> 00:06:35.250
But how close another object
can get before it's ripped apart

00:06:35.250 --> 00:06:37.250
by the tidal forces due
to a first object, which

00:06:37.250 --> 00:06:38.920
is due to gravitational
differentials,

00:06:38.920 --> 00:06:41.560
that turns out to depend on the
density of that second object.

00:06:41.560 --> 00:06:43.760
Look up Roche
limit on Wikipedia.

00:06:43.760 --> 00:06:46.180
R MH, Noah Fence,
Fat Lum, Gareth Dean,

00:06:46.180 --> 00:06:48.676
and Parrish Danforth all
asked in one way or another

00:06:48.676 --> 00:06:50.800
why the shell of the moon
wouldn't collapse and get

00:06:50.800 --> 00:06:52.020
sucked into the black hole.

00:06:52.020 --> 00:06:54.020
The short answer is that
black holes don't suck.

00:06:54.020 --> 00:06:56.314
In fact, far from their
horizon, which in this case

00:06:56.314 --> 00:06:58.230
would be just centimeters
since the horizon is

00:06:58.230 --> 00:07:00.021
sub-millimeter sized,
the fact that there's

00:07:00.021 --> 00:07:02.222
a black hole in play
becomes kind of irrelevant.

00:07:02.222 --> 00:07:03.930
If you have material
that's strong enough

00:07:03.930 --> 00:07:06.080
to withstand internal
stresses, you

00:07:06.080 --> 00:07:07.710
could put a shell
that just sits there

00:07:07.710 --> 00:07:09.877
around pretty much anything,
including a black hole.

00:07:09.877 --> 00:07:12.168
Chronoflect asked whether
Termina's moon could actually

00:07:12.168 --> 00:07:14.090
rip apart in the three
day window of the game

00:07:14.090 --> 00:07:15.630
if it were the density
of Earth's moon.

00:07:15.630 --> 00:07:17.171
It turns out that
time to disassembly

00:07:17.171 --> 00:07:19.280
versus time to impact is
a pretty tricky issue.

00:07:19.280 --> 00:07:20.950
A lot of factors come into play.

00:07:20.950 --> 00:07:22.450
I've seen this
modelled in the case

00:07:22.450 --> 00:07:24.899
of the Shoemaker-Levy comet
that hit Jupiter in 1994,

00:07:24.899 --> 00:07:27.190
but I don't recall whether
there's a definitive recipe.

00:07:27.190 --> 00:07:29.564
I think it depends a lot on
the details of the situation.

00:07:29.564 --> 00:07:31.049
Raphael Hviding
and Daniel Jenkins

00:07:31.049 --> 00:07:33.590
asked, wouldn't a black hole as
small as the one I'm claiming

00:07:33.590 --> 00:07:34.580
evaporate quickly?

00:07:34.580 --> 00:07:35.750
In relative terms, yes.

00:07:35.750 --> 00:07:38.290
But it would still take ten
thousand trillion trillion

00:07:38.290 --> 00:07:40.470
times the current age of
the universe to do so.

00:07:40.470 --> 00:07:42.720
Finally, Patrick Fadgen
asked, how can the moon be

00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:44.470
